# ERROR: System.NullReferenceException: Object reference not set to an instance of an object

## Platform
.NET / C# / VB.NET / ASP.NET

## Cause
This exception occurs when you try to access a member (property, method, indexer) on a reference type variable that is `null`. Common scenarios:

1. **Forgot to instantiate a reference type** - Declared a variable but never assigned an object to it
2. **Forgot to dimension an array** - Array declared but not initialized with a size
3. **Method returned null** - A method like `Array.Find()` or LINQ query returned null and you accessed it directly
4. **Chained expressions** - Intermediate value in a chain of property/method calls is null
5. **Enumerating array with null elements** - Array contains null elements that you're trying to use

## Quick Fix

### Step 1: Locate the null value
Set a breakpoint at the exception line and examine all variables:
```csharp
// Use the debugger to check which variable is null
// Hover over each variable in Visual Studio
```

### Step 2: Add null checks
```csharp
// Option 1: Traditional null check
if (myObject != null)
{
    myObject.DoSomething();
}

// Option 2: Null-conditional operator (C# 6+)
myObject?.DoSomething();

// Option 3: Null-coalescing operator
string name = myObject?.Name ?? "Default";
```

### Step 3: Initialize objects properly
```csharp
// Wrong - not initialized
List<string> names;
names.Add("John"); // NullReferenceException!

// Correct - initialized
List<string> names = new List<string>();
names.Add("John");
```

## PowerShell/Commands
```powershell
# Enable first-chance exception debugging in Visual Studio:
# Debug > Windows > Exception Settings
# Check "Common Language Runtime Exceptions"

# For ASP.NET Core, enable detailed errors in Development:
# Set ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT=Development
```

## C# Code Patterns
```csharp
// Pattern 1: Guard clauses at method start
public void Process(Customer customer)
{
    if (customer == null)
        throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(customer));

    // Safe to use customer now
}

// Pattern 2: Null-conditional + null-coalescing
string title = pages.CurrentPage?.Title ?? "No Title";

// Pattern 3: Check method return values
var found = Array.Find(items, x => x.Id == id);
if (found != null)
{
    Console.WriteLine(found.Name);
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Item not found");
}

// Pattern 4: Enable nullable reference types (C# 8+)
// In .csproj: <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
// Compiler will warn about potential null dereferences
```

## Prevention
1. **Enable Nullable Reference Types** (C# 8+) - Add `<Nullable>enable</Nullable>` to your .csproj
2. **Use ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull()** (.NET 6+) at method entry points
3. **Prefer the null-conditional operator `?.`** over manual null checks
4. **Initialize collections in field declarations** rather than constructors
5. **Always check return values** from methods that can return null
6. **Use pattern matching** for cleaner null checks: `if (obj is not null)`

