# ERROR: SyntaxError: await is only valid in async functions

## Cause
You used the `await` keyword outside of an `async` function. In JavaScript, `await` can only be used:
- Inside functions declared with `async`
- At the top level of ES modules (top-level await)

Common triggers:
- Forgot to add `async` to the function
- Using `await` in a callback that isn't async
- Using `await` in a regular script (not a module)

## Quick Fix
1. Add `async` keyword to the containing function
2. For callbacks (map, forEach, etc.), make the callback async
3. For top-level code, either wrap in an async IIFE or use ES modules
4. Consider if you actually need await or can use `.then()`

## Code Example
```javascript
// Before (broken) - missing async keyword
function fetchData() {
  const response = await fetch('/api/data');
  return response.json();
}
// SyntaxError: await is only valid in async functions

// After (fixed) - add async keyword
async function fetchData() {
  const response = await fetch('/api/data');
  return response.json();
}

// Before (broken) - await in non-async callback
const urls = ['/api/1', '/api/2'];
urls.forEach(url => {
  const data = await fetch(url);  // Error!
  console.log(data);
});

// After (fixed) - async callback + Promise.all
const urls = ['/api/1', '/api/2'];
await Promise.all(urls.map(async url => {
  const response = await fetch(url);
  const data = await response.json();
  console.log(data);
}));

// Before (broken) - top-level await in script
// <script src="app.js"></script>
const config = await fetch('/config.json');
// SyntaxError: await is only valid in async functions

// After (fixed) - Option 1: async IIFE
(async () => {
  const config = await fetch('/config.json');
  // rest of code
})();

// After (fixed) - Option 2: ES module (recommended)
// <script type="module" src="app.js"></script>
const config = await fetch('/config.json');  // Works in modules!

// Common gotcha: forEach doesn't wait
// Before (broken) - forEach ignores async
async function processAll(items) {
  items.forEach(async item => {
    await processItem(item);  // These run in parallel, not sequence!
  });
  console.log('Done');  // Logs before processing finishes!
}

// After (fixed) - use for...of for sequential
async function processAll(items) {
  for (const item of items) {
    await processItem(item);  // Sequential
  }
  console.log('Done');  // Logs after all done
}
```

## Prevention
- Always pair `await` with `async` function declarations
- Use ES modules (`<script type="module">`) for modern code
- Remember: `async` makes a function return a Promise
- Use `for...of` instead of `forEach` when you need sequential async operations
- Use `Promise.all()` with `map` for parallel async operations
- Consider using top-level await in Node.js with `"type": "module"` in package.json

# ERROR: Access to fetch blocked by CORS policy

Also appears as:
- `No 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' header is present`
- `CORS policy: No 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin'`
- `Cross-Origin Request Blocked`

## Cause
Browser security blocks requests to different domains unless the server explicitly allows it.

## Quick Fix

### If you control the server (Node/Express):
```javascript
// Install: npm install cors
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors()); // Allow all origins

// Or specific origins:
app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://yourdomain.com', 'http://localhost:3000']
}));
```

### If you control the server (Lambda/API Gateway):
Add these headers to your response:
```javascript
return {
  statusCode: 200,
  headers: {
    'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*',
    'Access-Control-Allow-Methods': 'GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS',
    'Access-Control-Allow-Headers': 'Content-Type, Authorization'
  },
  body: JSON.stringify(data)
};
```

### If you DON'T control the server:

**Option 1: Proxy through your backend**
```javascript
// Your server fetches the data, then serves it to your frontend
app.get('/api/proxy', async (req, res) => {
  const data = await fetch('https://external-api.com/data');
  res.json(await data.json());
});
```

**Option 2: Use a CORS proxy (development only)**
```javascript
fetch('https://cors-anywhere.herokuapp.com/https://api.example.com/data')
```

## Common Mistakes

### Forgetting OPTIONS preflight
For non-simple requests (POST with JSON, custom headers), browser sends OPTIONS first:
```javascript
// Handle OPTIONS in Lambda:
if (event.httpMethod === 'OPTIONS') {
  return { statusCode: 200, headers: corsHeaders, body: '' };
}
```

### Wrong header name
```javascript
// Wrong:
'Access-Control-Allow-Origins': '*'  // Note the 's'

// Right:
'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*'
```

## Prevention
- Always set CORS headers on your API from day 1
- Use environment-specific allowed origins (not `*` in production)
- Handle OPTIONS method explicitly

## Related Errors
- `Preflight request doesn't pass access control check`
- `Request header field X is not allowed`

