# React Hooks Rules Violations

## Error Messages

```
React Hook "useState" is called conditionally. React Hooks must be called in the exact same order in every component render.

React Hook "useEffect" is called in function "helper" that is neither a React function component nor a custom React Hook function.

React Hook "useMemo" cannot be called inside a callback. React Hooks must be called in a React function component or a custom React Hook function.

Rendered more hooks than during the previous render.
```

## The Rules of Hooks

1. **Only call hooks at the top level** — not inside loops, conditions, or nested functions
2. **Only call hooks from React functions** — components or custom hooks (functions starting with `use`)

## Why These Rules Exist

React tracks hooks by the order they're called. If the order changes between renders, React can't match state to the correct hook.

```
First render:  useState(0) → useEffect(...) → useMemo(...)
Second render: useState(0) → useMemo(...)    // 💥 Order changed!
```

## Fix

### ❌ Problem: Conditional Hook Call

```jsx
function Profile({ user }) {
  // 💥 Hook called conditionally
  if (user) {
    const [name, setName] = useState(user.name);
  }

  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

### ✅ Solution: Call Hook Unconditionally, Conditionally Use Result

```jsx
function Profile({ user }) {
  // ✅ Always called
  const [name, setName] = useState(user?.name ?? '');

  if (!user) return <div>No user</div>;

  return <div>{name}</div>;
}
```

### ❌ Problem: Hook Inside Loop

```jsx
function ItemList({ items }) {
  // 💥 Different number of hooks each render
  items.forEach(item => {
    const [selected, setSelected] = useState(false);
  });

  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>;
}
```

### ✅ Solution: Move to Child Component

```jsx
function ItemList({ items }) {
  return (
    <div>
      {items.map(item => (
        <Item key={item.id} item={item} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

function Item({ item }) {
  // ✅ Each Item has its own hook instance
  const [selected, setSelected] = useState(false);
  return <div onClick={() => setSelected(!selected)}>{item.name}</div>;
}
```

### ❌ Problem: Hook After Early Return

```jsx
function UserData({ userId }) {
  if (!userId) {
    return <div>No user ID</div>; // 💥 Hooks below won't be called
  }

  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);
  }, [userId]);

  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

### ✅ Solution: Hooks Before Any Returns

```jsx
function UserData({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (userId) {
      fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);
    }
  }, [userId]);

  // ✅ Early return after all hooks
  if (!userId) {
    return <div>No user ID</div>;
  }

  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

### ❌ Problem: Hook in Regular Function

```jsx
// 💥 Not a React component or custom hook
function helper() {
  const [state, setState] = useState(0); // Error!
  return state;
}

function MyComponent() {
  const value = helper();
  return <div>{value}</div>;
}
```

### ✅ Solution: Create Custom Hook

```jsx
