# ERROR: SyntaxError: Unexpected token

## Cause
JavaScript parser encountered a character or keyword where it wasn't expected. The code structure is invalid. Common triggers:

- **Trailing commas** in wrong places (older JS, JSON)
- **Missing parentheses/brackets/braces** - unbalanced delimiters
- **Typos in syntax** - `;` where `,` expected, etc.
- **Using reserved words** as identifiers
- **Object literal vs function body confusion**
- **Copy-paste errors** with invisible characters

## Quick Fix
1. Check the line number in the error - look at that line AND the one before it
2. Count your brackets/parentheses/braces - ensure they match
3. Remove trailing commas in arrays/objects (especially for JSON)
4. Check for missing colons in object literals
5. Verify you're using the right syntax for the context

## Code Example
```javascript
// Before (broken) - trailing comma in for loop
for (let i = 0; i < 5,; ++i) {
  console.log(i);
}
// SyntaxError: Unexpected token ';'

// After (fixed) - remove trailing comma
for (let i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {
  console.log(i);
}

// Before (broken) - missing outer parentheses in condition
if (n > 10) || (n < 0) {
  throw new Error("Out of range");
}
// SyntaxError: Unexpected token '||'

// After (fixed) - wrap entire condition
if ((n > 10) || (n < 0)) {
  throw new Error("Out of range");
}

// Before (broken) - object method without ()
const component = {
  mounted: {
    document.getElementById("app").classList.add("ready");
  }
}
// SyntaxError: Unexpected token '.'

// After (fixed) - proper method syntax
const component = {
  mounted() {
    document.getElementById("app").classList.add("ready");
  }
}

// Before (broken) - missing colon in object
const obj = { foo 1, bar: 2 };
// SyntaxError: Unexpected number

// After (fixed) - add colon
const obj = { foo: 1, bar: 2 };
```

## Prevention
- Use a code editor with syntax highlighting and bracket matching
- Use Prettier or similar formatter to auto-fix syntax issues
- Use ESLint to catch syntax errors before runtime
- When copy-pasting code, watch for invisible/special characters
- Check MDN or documentation when unsure about syntax
- The error often points to where the parser got confused - the actual mistake may be earlier

